You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` using `OnNavigating` + `GetDeferral()`, and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with cancel logic

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Discard changes?",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return;
        }

        HasUnsavedChanges = false; // let the guard pass
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Navigation guard in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

This catches the **system back button / swipe-back gesture** (which bypasses `BackButtonBehavior.Command`):

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Discard changes?",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();
        else
            vm.HasUnsavedChanges = false;

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`BackButtonBehavior.Command`** handles the Shell back button tap; `OnNavigating` handles the hardware/gesture back.
- Setting `HasUnsavedChanges = false` before navigating in `CancelCommand` prevents the guard from showing a second dialog.
